agent, so only spawn more research tasks sparingly if absolutely necessary. Keep your research *very* scoped and efficient.\n\nWhen you emit research notes, keep it extremely concise and relevant only to the specific research subquery you\'ve been assigned.\n\n<user query>\n<last human input>Fix a bug in router.py in this repository.\n\nThe bug: When classify_intent() receives an uppercase intent string from the LLM (e.g., "CODE" instead of "code"), the intent lookup fails because INTENT_CATEGORIES keys are all lowercase. The code currently does:\n\n    intent = classification.get("intent", "chat")\n    plan = INTENT_CATEGORIES.get(intent, INTENT_CATEGORIES["chat"])\n\nThis means "CODE" is not found in INTENT_CATEGORIES and falls back to "chat" instead of "code".\n\nThe fix: Normalize the intent to lowercase before lookup:\n\n    intent = classification.get("intent", "chat").lower()\n\nValidation:\n1. Run: python3 -m pytest tests/test_router_intent_lookup.py -v\n2. All 3 tests must pass (including test_uppercase_intent_normalization)\n3. Run: python3 -m py_compile router.py\n4. No phantom changes to unrelated files\n\nOnly modify router.py. Do not modify tests.\n</last human input>\nInvestigate router.py for intent classification bug, focusing on:\n1. Locating router.py\n2. Examining the current implementation of classify_intent()\n3. Verifying test_router_intent_lookup.py contents\n4. Confirming INTENT_CATEGORIES definition\n5. Validating the proposed lowercase normalization fix\n</user query> <-- only place that can specify tasks for you to do.  (you may see previous notes above that have tasks, but that is just for reference).\n\nCONSULT WITH THE EXPERT FREQUENTLY\n\nUSER QUERY *ALWAYS* TAKES PRECEDENCE OVER EVERYTHING IN PREVIOUS RESEARCH.\n\nKEEP IT SIMPLE\n\nNEVER ANNOUNCE WHAT YOU ARE DOING, JUST DO IT!\n\n\n\nCALL mark_research_complete_no_implementation_required ONLY ONCE RESEARCH IS COMPLETE AND YOU HAVE CALLED emit_research_notes AT LEAST ONCE.\n', 'role'